text=BOOK XXL %0a%0aAN ACCOUNT OF FLOWERS, AND THOSE USED FOR %0aCHAPLETS MORE PARTICULARLY. %0a%0aCHAP, 1 . ( 1 .) —the NATUKE OF FLOWERS AND GARLANDS. %0a%0aCato has recommended that flow'ers for raaJring chaplets %0ashould also be cultivated in the garden ; varieties remarkable %0afor a delicacy which it is quite impossible to express, inas¬ %0amuch as no individual can find such facilities for describing %0athem as Nature does for bestowing on them their numerous tints %0a—Nature, who here in especial shows herself in a sportive %0amood, and takes a delight in the prolific display of her varied %0aproductions. The other' plants she has produced for our use %0aand our nutriment, and to them accordingly she has granted %0ayears and even ages of duration : but as for the fiowers and %0atheir perfumes, she has given them birth for but a day—a %0amighty lesson to man, we see, to teach him that that which in %0aits career is the most beauteous and the most attractive to the %0aeye, is the very first to fade and die. %0a%0aEven the limner’s art itself possesses no resources for re¬ %0aproducing the colours of the fiowers in all their varied tints %0aand combinations, whether we view them in groups alter¬ %0anately blending their hues, or whether arranged in festoons, each %0avariety by * itself, now assuming a circular form, now running %0aobliquely, and now disposed in a spiral pattern ; or whether, %0aas we see sometimes, one wreath is interwoven within another. %0a%0aCHAP. 2 . ( 2 .) —GARLANDS AND CHAPLETS. %0a%0aThe ancients used chaplets of diminutive size, called %0a“ struppifrom which comes our name for a chaplet, “ stro- %0a%0a* See B. xxii. c. 1. %0a%0a2 “ Sive privatis generum funiculis in orbem, in obliquum, in ambitnm ; %0aquaedam coronae per coronas currunt.” As we know but little of tbe forms %0aof the garlands and chaplets of tbe ancients, the exact translation of this %0apassage is very doubtful. %0a%0a^ According to Boettiger, the w'ord “ struppus ” means a string arranged %0aos a fillet or diadem. ' %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 3.] %0a%0a%0aTHK ART OF MAKING GARLANDS. %0a%0a%0a305 %0a%0a%0aphiolum.” Indeed, it was only by very slow degrees that %0athis last word"* became generalized, as the chaplets that were %0aused at sacrifices, or were granted as the reward of militaiy %0avalour, asserted their exclusive right to the name of “ corona.” %0aAs for garlands, Avhen they came to be made of flowers, they %0areceived the name of “ serta,” from the verb “ sero,”® or %0aelse from our word “ series.”® The use’ of flowers for gar¬ %0alands is not so very ancient, among the Greeks even. %0a%0aCUAP. 3. — WHO INVENTED THE ART OF MAKING GARLANDS : %0a%0aWHEN THEY FIRST RECEIVED THE NAME OF “ COROLL.®,” AND %0a%0aFOR WHAT REASON. %0a%0aFor in early times it was the usage to crown the victors in %0athe sacred contests with branches of trees: and it was only %0aat a later period, that they began to vary their tints by the %0acombination® of flowers, to heighten the effect in turn by their %0acolour and their smell—an invention due to the ingenuity of %0athe painter Pausias, at Sicyon,® and the garland-maker Gly- %0acera, a female to whom he was greatly attached, and. whose %0ahandiwork was imitated by him in colours. Challenging him %0ato a trial of skill, she would repeatedly vary her designs, and %0athus it was in reality a contest between art and Nature ; a fact %0awhich we find attested by pictures of that artist even still in %0aexistence, more particularly the one known as the “ Stephane- %0al»locos,”'“ in which he has given a likeness of Glycera herself. %0aThis invention, therefore, is only to be traced to later than the %0aHundredth’’ Olympiad. %0a%0aChaplets of flowers being now the fashion, it Avas not long %0abefore those came into vogue which are known to us as %0a%0a^ Fee makes the word “vocahulum” apply to “corona,” and not to %0a“ struppns but the passage will hardly admit of that rendering. %0a%0a* “To bind” or “join together.’’ %0a%0a® A “ connected line,” from the verb “ sero.” %0a%0a’ By “quod,” Hardouin takes Pliny to mean, the use of the word %0aciraprbv, among the Greeks, corresponding with the Latin word “ sertum.” %0a%0a** These chaplets, we learn from Festus, were called “ pancarpiae.” %0aThe olive, oak, laurel, and myrtle, were the trees first used for chaplets. %0a%0a® See B. ixxv. c. 40. %0a%0a. *® The “ Chaplet-weaver.” See B. xxxv. c. 40. %0a%0a” B.C. 380. %0a%0aTOL. IV. %0a%0a%0aX %0a%0a%0a306 %0a%0a%0aPLINr’s NATUBAL IlISTOBY. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXI. %0a%0a%0aEgyptian*^ chaplets; and then the winter chaplets, made for %0athe time at which Earth refuses her flowers, of thin laminae of %0ahorn stained various colours. By slow degrees, too, the name %0awas introduced at Borne, these garlands being known there %0aat first as “ corollae,” a designation given them to express %0athe remarkable delicacy of their texture. In more recent %0atimes, again, when the chaplets presented were made of thin %0aplates of copper, gilt or silvered, they assumed the name %0aof “ corollaria.” %0a%0aCHAP. 4 . ( 3 .) —WHO WAS THE FIRST TO GIVE CHAPLETS WITH %0aLEAVES OF silver AND GOLD. LEMNISCI : WHO WAS THE FIRST %0aTO EMBOSS THEM. %0a%0aCrassus Dives was the first who gave chaplets with arti¬ %0aficial leaves of silver and gold, at the games celebrated by him. %0aTo embellish these chaplets, and to confer additional honour %0aon them, lemnisci were added, in imitation of the Etruscan %0achaplets, which ought properly to have none but lemnisci %0amade of gold. For a long period these lemnisci were desti¬ %0atute of ornament P. Claudius Pulcher*® was the first who %0ataught us to emboss*® them, and added leaves of tinsel to the %0alaminee®® of which the lemniscus was formed. %0a%0aCHAP. 5 . —THE GREAT HONOUR IN WHICH CHAPLETS WERE HELD %0aBY THE ANCIENTS. %0a%0aChaplets, however, were always held in a high degree of %0aestimation, those even which were acquired at the public %0agames. For it was the usage of the citizens to go down in %0aperson to take part in the contests of the Circus, and to %0asend their slaves and horses thither as well. Hence it is that %0awe find it thus written in the laws of the Twelve Tables: %0a%0a12 From Atlienoeus, B. xv. c. 2, et seq., we learn that the Egyptian %0achaplets were made of ivy, narcissus, pomegranate blossoms, &c. %0a%0a‘2 “Corolla,” being the diminutive of “corona.” %0a%0a1* Or tinsel. is The “ Rich.” %0a%0aIS Ribbons or streamers. i^ “Puri.” %0a%0aIS Consul, A.u.c. 570. %0a%0aIS Or “engrave,” “caelare.” Jle is probably speaking here of golden %0alemnisci. %0a%0a20 “ Philyr®.” This was properly the inner bark of the linden-tree; %0abut it is not improbable that thin plates of metal were also so called, from %0ache resemblance. The passage, however, admits of various modes of ex¬ %0aplanation. %0a%0a*• 1 %0a%0a%0aChap. 6.] %0a%0a%0aCHAPLETS. %0a%0a%0a307 %0a%0a%0a“ If any person has gained a chaplet himself, or by his %0amoney,** let the same be given to him as the reward of his %0aprowess.” There is no doubt that by the words “ gained by %0ahis money,” the laws meant a chaplet which had been gained %0aby his slaves or horses. Well then, what was the honour ac¬ %0aquired thereby ? It was the right secured bythe victor, for %0ahimself and for his parents, after death, to be crowned with¬ %0aout fail, while the body was laid out in the house,** and on its %0abeing carried** to the tomb. %0a%0aOn other occasions, chaplets were not indiscriminately %0aworn, not even those which had been won in the games. %0a%0aCHAP. 6.-THE SEVERITY OF THE AHCIEHTS IN REFERENCE TO %0a%0aCHAPLETS. %0a%0aIndeed the rules upon this point were remarkably severe. %0aL. Fulvius, a banker,** having been accused, at the time of %0athe Second Punic War, of looking down from the balcony*® %0aof his house upon the Forum, with a chaplet of roses upon %0ahis head, was imprisoned by order of the Senate, and was not %0aliberated before the war was brought to a close. P. Muna- %0atius, having placed upon his head a chaplet of flowers taken %0afrom the statue of Marsyas,*® was condemned by the Trium¬ %0aviri to be put in chains. Upon his making appeal to the %0atribunes of the people, they refused to intercede in his behalf %0a—a very different state of things to that at Athens, where %0athe young men,*’ in their dnmken revelry, were in the habit, %0a%0a** “ Pecunia.” Fee compares this usage with the employment of jockies %0aat horse-races in England and France. %0a%0a“ Intus positus esset.” •* “ Foris ferretur.” %0a%0a2* Or “ money-changer,” ‘‘ argentarius.” %0a%0a“ “E pergula sua.” Scaliger thinks that the “pergula” was a part %0aof a house built out into the street, while, according to Ernesti,^ it was a %0alittle room in the upper part of a house. In B. xxxv. c. 36, it clearly %0ameans a room on the ground-floor. %0a%0a26 In the Fora of ancient cities there was frequently a statue of this my¬ %0athological personage, with one hand erect, in token, Servius says (on %0aB. iv. 1. 58 of the iEneid), of the freedom of the state, Marsyas having been %0athe minister of Bacchus, the god of liberty. His statue in the Forum of %0aRome was the place of assembly for the courtesans of that city, who used %0ato crown it with chaplets ot flow’crs. See also Horace i. Sat. 6. 1. 120; %0aJuvenal, Sat. 9. 1. 1 and 2; and Martial,ii. Ep. 64.1. 7. %0a%0a27 Ciijacius thinks that Pliny has in view here Polemon of Athens, who %0awhen a young man, in his drunken revelry, burst into the school of Xeno- %0acratcs. the philosopher, with his fellow-revellers, wearing his festive gar- %0a%0a%0aPLIXT’S XATUKAIi lIISrOKT. [Book XXI. %0a%0abefore midday, of making their way into the very schools of %0athe philosophers even. Among ourselves, no such instance of %0aa similar licentiousness is lo be found, unless, indeed, in the %0acase of the daughter*® of the late Emperor Augustus, who, in %0aher nocturnal debaucheries, placed a chaplet on the statue^* %0aof JIarsyas, conduct deeply deplored in the letters of that %0agod.®" %0a%0aCHAP. 7.-A CITIZEN DECKED WITH FLOWEES BY THE HOMAN %0a%0aPEOPLE. %0a%0aScipio is the only person that ever received from the Eoman %0apeople the honour of being decked with flowers. This %0aScipio received the surname of Serapio,®^ from his remarkable %0aresemblance to a certain person of that name who dealt in %0apigs. He died in his tribuneship, greatly beloved by the %0apeople, and in every way worthy of the family of the African!. %0aThe property he left was not sufficient to pay the expenses of %0ahis burial; upon which the people made a subscription and %0acontracted®* for his funeral, flowers being scattered upon the %0abody from every possible quarter®® as it was borne along. %0a%0aCUAP. 8. — PLAITED CHAPLETS. NEEDLE-WORK CHAPLETS. %0a%0aNARD-LEAF CHAPLETS. SILKEN CHAPLETS. %0a%0aIn those days, too, chaplets were employed in honour of the %0agods, the Lares, public as well as domestic, the sepulchres,®* %0aand the Manes. The highest place, however, in public esti¬ %0amation, was held by the plaited chaplet; such as we find used %0a%0aland on his head. Being arrested, however, by the discourse, he stopped %0ato listen, and at length, tearing off the garland, determined to enter on a %0amore abstemious course of life. Becoming an ardent disciple of Xeno- %0acrates, he ultimately succeeded him at the head of the school. The pas¬ %0asage as given in the text, from its apparent incompleteness, would appear %0ato he in a mutilated state. %0a%0a^ Julia. See B. vii. c. 46. %0a%0a*9 Thus acknowledging herself to be no better than a common courtesan. %0a“ lUius dei.” 3‘ See B. vii. c. 10. %0a%0a32 “ Funus elocavit.” %0a%0a33 “ E prospectu omni.” “ From every look-out i.e. from the roofs, %0adoors, and windows. %0a%0a3* This usage is still observed in the immortelles, laid on the tombs of %0adeparted friends, in Catholic countries on the continent. Tibullus alludes %0ato it, B. ii. El. 4: %0a%0a“ Atque aliquis senior veteres veneratus amores, %0a%0aAnnua constructo serta dabit tumulo.” %0a%0a%0aChap. 9.] %0a%0a%0aCHAPLETS. %0a%0a%0a309 %0a%0a%0aby tlie Salii in their sacred rites, and at the solemnization of %0atheir yearly^® banquets. In later times, the rose chaplet has %0abeen adopted, and luxury arose at last to such a pitch that a %0achaplet was held in no esteem at all if it did not consist en¬ %0atirely of leaves sown together with the needle. More recently, %0aagain, they have been imported from India, or from nations %0abeyond the countries of India. %0a%0aBut it is looked upon as the most refined of all, to present %0achaplets made of nard leaves, or else of silk of many colours %0asteeped in unguents. Such is the pitch to which the luxu¬ %0ariousness of our women has at last arrived! %0a%0aCHAP. 9.-AHTHORS WHO HAVE WRITTEN ON FLOWERS. AN %0a%0aANECDOTE RELATIVE TO Q0EEN CLEOPATRA AND CHAPLETS. %0a%0aAmong the Greeks, the physicians Mnesitheus and Calli¬ %0amachus have written separate treatises on the subject of %0achaplets, making mention of such flowers as are injurious to %0athe head.®® For, in fact, the health is here concerned to some %0aextent, as it is at the moments of carousal and gaiety in par¬ %0aticular that penetrating odours steal insidiously upon the %0abrain—witness an instance in the wicked cunning displayed %0aupon one occasion by Cleopatra. %0a%0aAt the time when preparations were making for the battle %0athat was eventually fought at Actiura, Antonius held the %0aqueen in such extreme distrust as to be in dread of her very %0aattentions even, and would not so much as touch his food, %0aunless another person had tasted it first. Upon this, the %0aqueen, it is said, wishing to amuse herself with his fears, had %0a- the extremities of the flowers in a chaplet dipped in poison, and %0athen placed it upon her head.®^ After a time, as the hilarity %0aincreased apace, she challenged Antonius to swallow the chap¬ %0aes At the conclusion of the festival of Mars on the 1st of March, and %0afor several successive days. These entertainments were celebrated in the %0aTemple of that god, and were proverbial for their excellence. %0a%0a“ It is a well-known fact, as Fee remarks, that the smell of flowers is %0aproductive, in some persons, of head-ache, nausea, and vertigo. He states %0aalso that persons have been known to meet their death from sleeping all %0anight in the midst of odoriferous flowers. %0a%0a“Ipsaque capiti imposita.” Holland and Ajasson render this as %0atlioimh Cleopatra placed the garland on Antony’s head, and not her owu. %0aLittr'^ agrees with the translation here adopted. %0a%0a%0a310 %0a%0a%0aPliny’s natubal histoey. %0a%0a%0a[nook XXI. %0a%0a%0alets, mixed up with their drink. Who, under such circumstances %0aas these, could have apprehended treachery? Accordingly, %0athe leaves were stripped from off the chaplet, and thrown into %0aihe cup. Just as Antonius was on the very point of drinking, %0ashe arrested his arm with her hand.—“ Behold, Marcus An¬ %0atonius,” said she, “ the woman against whom you are so care¬ %0aful to take these new precautions of yours in employing your %0atasters! And would then, if I could exist without you, either %0ameans or opportunity of effecting my purpose be wanting to %0ame?” Saying this, she ordered a man to be brought from %0aprison, and made him drink off the potion; he did so, and %0afell dead®® upon the spot. %0a%0aBesides the two authors above-mentioned, Theophrastus,®* %0aamong the Greeks, has written on the subject of flowers. %0aSome of our own writers also have given the title of “ Antho- %0alogica” to their works, but no one, to my knowledge at least, %0ahas treated expressly^® of flowers. In fact, we ourselves have %0ano intention here of discussing the mode of wearing chaplets, %0afor that would be frivolous^^ indeed ; but shall proceed to %0astate such particulars in relation to flowers as shall appear to %0aus deserving of remark. %0a%0aCHAP. 10 . ( 4 .) —THE EOSE : TWELVE VAEIETIES OF IT. %0a%0aThe people of our country were acquainted with but very %0afew garland flowers among the garden plants, and those few %0ahardly any but the violet and the rose. The plant which bears %0athe rose is, properly speaking, more of a thorn than a shrub— %0aindeed, we sometimes find it growing on a bramble^* even; %0athe flower having, even then, a pleasant smell, though by no %0ameans penetrating. The flower in all roses is originally en¬ %0aclosed in a bud,^® with a grained surface within, which gra¬ %0adually swells, and assumes the form of a green pointed cone, %0asimilar to our alabaster^^ unguent boxes in shape. Gradually %0a%0aFee remarks that we know of no poisons, hydrocyanic or prussic acid %0aexcepted, so instantaneous in their effects as this; and that it is very %0adoubtful if they were acquainted with that poison. %0a%0aHist. Plant. B. vi. cc. 6, 7. “ Persecutus est.” %0a%0aA characteristic, it would appear, of the greater part of the inform¬ %0aation already given in this Book. %0a%0aHe alludes to the wild rose or eglantine. See B. xvi. c. 71. %0a%0a“ Granoso cortice.” %0a%0a^ Boxes of a pyramidal shape. See B. ix. c. 56. %0a%0a%0aChap. 10.1 %0a%0a%0aTHE HOSE. %0a%0a%0a311 %0a%0a%0aacquiring a ruddy tint, this bud opens little by little, until at %0alast it comes into full blow, developing the calyx, and em¬ %0abracing the yellow-pointed filaments which stand erect in the %0acentre of it. %0a%0aThe employment of the rose in chaplets is, so to say, the %0aleast^® use that is made of it. The flower is steeped in oil, a %0apractice which has prevailed from the times of the Trojan war, %0aas Homer‘® bears witness; in addition to which, it now forms %0aan ingredient in our unguents, as mentioned on a previous %0aoccasion.^^ It is employed also by itself for certain medicinal %0apurposes, and is used in plasters and eye-salves^* for its pene¬ %0atrating qualities : it is used, also, to perfume the delicacies of %0aour banquets, and is never attended with any noxious results. %0a%0aThe most esteemed kinds of rose among us are those of %0aPrseneste'** and Campania.®* Some persons have added to these %0avarieties the rose of Miletus,®^ the flower of which is an ex¬ %0atremely brilliant red, and has never more than a dozen petals. %0aThe next to it is the rose of TrachjTi,®* not so red as the last, %0aand then that of Alabanda,®® with whitish petals, but not so %0ahighly esteemed. The least esteemed of all, however, is the %0athorn rose,®^ the petals of which are numerous, but extremely %0a%0aStill, even for that purpose the rose Avas very extensively used. One %0aancient author states that, even in the middle of winter, the more luxurious %0aliomans were not satisfied without roses swimming in their Falernian wine; %0aand we find Horace repeatedly alluding to the chaplets of roses worn by %0athe guests at banquets. Hence probably arose the expression, “Under %0athe rose.” Fee is evidently mistaken in thinking that Pliny implies here, %0athat it was but rarely used in chaplets. %0a%0aII. xxiii. 1. 186. B. xiii. c. 2. %0a%0a“Collyriis.” %0a%0aClusius Avas of opinion that this was the Provence rose, the Rosa %0aGallica of Uinnaeus. %0a%0aThe same rose, probably, of which Virgil says, Georg. B. iv. 1. 119, %0a“ Bifcrique rosaria Paesti”—" And the rose-beds of Paestum, that bear %0atwice in the year.” It has been suggested that it is identical with the %0aBosa alba vulgaris major of Bauhin, the Rosa alba of Decandolle; but, %0aas F4e says, it is very questionable if this is correct, this white rose blossom¬ %0aing but once a year. _ . i i %0a%0aA simple variety of the Rosa Gallica of Linnaeus, Fee thinks. %0a%0aSee B. iv. c. 14. According to J. Bauhin, this is the pale, flesh- %0acoloured rose, called the “ rose of France,”—the “ Rosa rubello flore, %0amajore, pleno, incarnata vulgo.’’ Others, again, take it to be the Damascus %0arose. %0a%0a“ Sec B. V. c. 29. A variety of the white rose, F^e thinks, the de¬ %0atermination of Avhich must be sought among the Eglantines. %0a%0a^ “Spiniola.” A variety belonging to or approaching the Eglantine %0a%0a%0a312 %0a%0a%0aPL,^^■r’s NATUEAL HI3T0UT. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXI. %0a%0a%0asmall. The essential points of difference in the rose are the %0anumber*^ of the petals, the comparative number*® of thorns on %0athe stem, the colour, and the smelj.. The number of the petals, %0awhich is never less than five, goes on increasing in amount, %0atill we find one variety with as many as a hundred, and %0athence known as the “ centifolia :”*■ in Italy, it is to be found %0ain Campania, and in Greece, in the vicinity of Philippi, though %0athis last is not the place of its natural*® growth. Mount Pan- %0agaeus,*® in the same vicinity, produces a rose with numerous %0apetals of diminutive size : the people of those parts are in the %0ahabit of transplanting it, a method which greatly tends to im¬ %0aprove its growth. This kind, however, is not remarkable for %0aits smell, nor yet is the rose which has a very large or very %0abroad petal: indeed, we may state in a few words, that the %0abest proof of the perfume of the flower is the comparative %0aroughness of the calyx.®® %0a%0aCaepio, who lived in the reign of the Emperor Tiberius, as¬ %0aserts that the centifolia is never employed for chaplets, except %0aat the extreme®^ points of union as it were, being remarkable %0aneither for its smelF nor its beauty. There is another variety %0a%0ain all probability. Fee makes mention here of a kind called the Rosa %0amyriacantha by Decandolle (the “ thousand-thornrose”), which is found in %0agreat abundance in the south of Europe, and other parts of it. %0a%0aFee remarks on this passage, that the beauty of the flower and the %0anumber of the petals are always in an inverse proportion to the number of %0athorns, which disappear successively the more carefully the plant is culti¬ %0avated. %0a%0a5’ This is most probably the meaning of “ Aspcritate, levore.” %0a%0aStill known as the Rosa centifolia.” Its petals sometimes exceed %0athree hundred in number ; and it is the most esteemed of all for its frag¬ %0arant smell. %0a%0a“ Non suae terrae proventu.” %0a%0aThis rose is mentioned also by Theophrastus, Hist. Plant. B. vi. c, 6. %0aFrom the description that Pliny gives of it. Fee is inclined to think that %0ait is some variety of the Rosa rubrifolia, which is often found in moun¬ %0atainous localities. %0a%0aThis assertion is borrowed from Theophrastus, Hist. Plant. B. vi. c. %0a6. Fee remarks that there is no truth in it. It is not improbable, how¬ %0aever, that the word “cortex” here may mean, not the calyx, but the bark %0aof the stem, in reference to its exemptiom from thorns. The to %0a%0aKUTw of Theophrastus would seem to admit of that rendering. See Note %0a^ above. %0a%0a“ Extremes velut ad cardines.” %0a%0aThis is not the case with the Rosa centifolia of modern botany. See %0aNote above. It is not improbable, however, that the reading is “pro- %0ababilis,” and that this passage belongs to the next sentence. %0a%0a%0aChap. 10.] • %0a%0a%0aTHE BOSE. %0a%0a%0a313 %0a%0a%0aof rose, too, called the “Grecian” rose by our people, and %0a“ lychnis by the Greeks: it grows nowhere except in %0ahumid soils, and has never more than five petals: it does not %0aexceed the violet in size, and is destitute of smell. There is %0aanother kind, again, known to us as the “ Grsecula,” the %0apetals of which are tightly rolled together, and which never %0aopen except when pressed in the hand, it having always the %0aappearance, in fact, of being in bud: the petals of it are re¬ %0amarkably large. Another kind, again, springs from a stem %0alike that of the mallow, the leaves being similar to those of %0athe olive—the name given to it is “ macetum.”®® There is %0athe rose of autumn, too, known to us as the “ coroniola,”®® %0aM'hich is of a middle size, between the variet