o.'® %0a%0aSee c. 38 of this Book; also B. xvi. c. 31. %0a%0aFrom the herb “hysge,” used for dyeing a deep red. See B. ix. c. %0a65, and B. xxi. c. 36. No such colour, Fee says, can be obtained fiom %0athe petals of either the Lilium Martagon or the Gladiolus communis, with %0awhich it has been identified. %0a%0a” It has no such effect; and the slave-dealers certainly lost their pains %0ain cosmetizing their slaves with it, their object being to^ make them look %0ayounger than they really were, and not older, as Hardouin seems to think. %0a%0aSee c. 10 of this Book. %0a%0a'» White specks in the pupil of the eye, or whiteness of the cornea. %0a%0a%0a382 plint’s nattthal history. [Book XXL %0a%0aCHAP. 99. (27.) —FOUR REMEDIES DERIVED FROM THE VINCA- %0aPERVINCA. %0a%0aThe vincapervinca,“ too, or chamaedaphne,** is dried and %0apounded, and given to dropsical patients in water, in doses of %0aone spoonful; a method of treatment which speedily draws off %0athe water. A decoction of it, in ashes, with a sprinkUng of %0awine, has the effect of drying tumours : the juice, too, is em¬ %0aployed as a remedy for diseases of the ears. Applied to the %0aregions of the stomach, this plant is said to be remarkably %0agood for diarrhoea. %0a%0aCHAP. 100. -THREE REMEDIES DERIVED FROM BDTCHEr’s BROOM. %0a%0aA decoction of the root of butcher’s broom“ is recommended to %0abe taken every other day for calculus in the bladder, strangury, %0aand bloody urine. The root, however, should be taken up %0aone day, and boiled the next, the proportion of it being one %0asextarius to two cyathi of wine. Some persons beat up the %0aroot raw, and take it in water; it is generally considered, too, %0athat there is nothing in existence more beneficial to the male %0aorgans than the young stalks of the plant, beaten up and used %0awith vinegar. ' %0a%0aCHAP. 101. —TWO REMEDIES DERIVED FROM THE BATIS. %0a%0aThe batis,^® too, relaxes the bowels, and, beaten up raw, %0ait is employed topically for the gout. The people of Egypt %0acultivate the acinos,*^ too, both as an article of food and for %0amaking chaplets. This plant would be the same thing as %0aocimum, were it not that the leaves and branches of it are %0arougher, and that it has a powerful smell. It promotes the %0acatamenia, and acts as a diuretic. %0a%0aCHAP. 102.(28.) -TWO REMEDIES DERIVED FROM THE COLOCASIA. %0a%0aThe colocasia,^® according to Glaucias, softens the acridity of %0ahumours of the body, and is beneficial to the stomach. %0a%0aSee c. 39 of this Book. “ Ground-laurel.” %0a%0a** See c. 50, and B. xxiii. c. 83. The medicinal properties of this plant %0aare not developed to any great extent; but it was thought till lately, Fee %0asays, to be an excellent diuretic. ^3 gge c. 49 andB. xxvi. c. 50. %0a%0aThe Thymus acinos of Linneeus. %0a%0aSee c. 51 of this Book. It is an alimentary plant, but eaten raw, it %0ais possessed of some acridity. %0a%0a%0aChap. 104.] TUE PABTHENIUM, LEUCANTHES, OK AMAEACUS. 383 %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 103. (29.) —SIX EEMEDIES DEEIVED FBOM THE ANTHYL- %0aLIUM OE ANTHYLLEM. %0a%0aThe people of Egypt eat the anthalium,*® but I cannot find %0athat they make any other use of it; but there is another plant %0acalled the “ anthyllium,”^’ or, by some persons, the “anthyl- %0alura,” of which there are two kinds : one, similar in its leaves %0aand branches to the lentil, a palm in height, growing in sandy %0asoils exposed to the sun, and of a somewhat saltish taste; the %0aother, bearing a strong resemblance to the chamsepitys,**® but %0asmaller and more downj’, with a purple fiower, a strong smell, %0aand growing in stony spots. %0a%0aThe first kind, mixed with rose-oil and applied with milk, %0ais extremely good for affections of the uterus and all kinds of %0asores : it is taken as a potion for strangury and gravel in the %0akidneys, in doses of three drachmae. The other kind is taken %0ain drink, with oxymel, in doses of four drachmae, for indura¬ %0ations of the uterus, gripings of the bowels, and epilepsy. %0a%0aCHAP. 104. (30.) -EIGHT EEMEDIES DEEIVED FEOM THE PAKTHE- %0a%0aNII7M, LEUCANTHES, OE AMAEACUS. %0a%0aThe parthenium®* is by some persons called the “leucan- %0athes,” and by others the “ amaracus.” Celsus, among the %0aLatin writers, gives it the names of “ perdicium”®® and “mu- %0aralis.” It grows in the hedge-rows of gardens, and has the %0asmell of an apple, with a bitter taste. With the decoction of %0ait, fomentations are made for maladies of the fundament, and %0afor inflammations and indurations of the uterus: dried and %0aapplied with honey and vinegar, it carries off black bile, for %0awhich reason it is considered good for vertigo and calculus in %0athe bladder. It is employed as a liniment, also, for erysipe¬ %0alas, and, mixed with stale axle-grease, for scrofulous sores. %0aFor tertian fevers the Magi recommend that it should be %0ataken up with the left hand, it being mentioned at the time %0afor whom it is gathered, care being also taken not to look back %0a%0a“ The C 3 rperus esculentus of Linnieus, the esculent souchet. %0a%0aThe two varieties are identified with the Cressa Cretica and the %0aTeucrium iva of Linnaeus. The latter plant is said to be a sudorific. %0a%0aSee B. xxvi. c. 53. %0a%0aThe Matricaria parthenium of Linnaeus. See c. 52. %0a%0aDe Be Med. ii. 33. It must not be confounded with the plant of %0athat name mentioned in c. 62 of this Book. %0a%0a%0a384 %0a%0a%0aPliny’s natueal histoet. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXI. %0a%0a%0awhile doing so : a leaf of it should be laid beneath the patient’s %0atongue, after which it must be eaten in a cyathus of water. %0a%0aCHAP. 105. (31.) —EIGHT KEMEDIES BEEITED FEOM THE TETCH- %0a%0aNUM OE STETCHNUM, HALICACABUM, CALLIAS, DOECYNION, %0a%0aMANICON, NEITEAS, MOKIO, OE MOLT. %0a%0aThe trychnon®^ is by some called “ strychnonI only wish %0athat the garland-makers of Egypt would never use this plant %0ain making their chaplets, being deceived as they are by the %0aresemblance in the leaves of both kinds to those of ivy. One %0aof these kinds, bearing scarlet berries with a stone, enclosed %0ain follicules, is by some persons called the “halicacabum,”^" by %0aothers the “ callion,” and by the people of our country, the %0a“ vesicaria,” from the circumstance of its being highly bene¬ %0aficial to the bladder^^ and in cases of calculus. %0a%0aThe trychnon is more of a woody shrub than a herb, with %0alarge follicules, broad and turbinated, and a large berry within, %0awhich ripens in the month of November. A thirdkind, %0aagain, has a leaf resembling that of ocimum—but it is not my %0aintention to give an exact description of it, as I am here speak¬ %0aing of remedies, and not of poisons; for a few drops of the %0ajuice, in fact, are quite sufficient to produce insanity. The %0aGreek writers, however, have even turned this property into %0amatter for jesting; for, according to them, taken in doses of %0aone drachma, this plant is productive of delusive and prurient %0afancies, and of vain, fantastic visions, which vividly present all %0athe appearance of reality: they say, too, that if the dose is %0adoubled, it will produce downright madness, and that any fur¬ %0ather addition to it, will result in instant death. %0a%0aThis is the same plant which the more well-meaning writem %0ahave called in their innocence “ dorycnion,”^® from the circum¬ %0astance that weapons used in battle are poisoned with it—for it %0agrows everywhere—while others, again, who have treated of it %0a%0aThe Solamim nigrum of Linnmus, or black night-shade. See B. %0aixiii. c. 108. %0a%0a*** The Physalis alkekengi of Linnseus; red night-shade, alkekengi, or %0a■winter cherry. Fee remarks, that the varieties of this plant in Egypt are %0avery numerous, and that in many places, till very recently, it was em¬ %0aployed as an article of food. 3^ “ Vesica.” %0a%0a3* The Solanum villosum of Lamarck. %0a%0a33 From Sopii, a “ spear.” %0a%0a%0aCliap. lOo.l %0a%0a%0aTHE halicacabum:. %0a%0a%0a385 %0a%0a%0amore at length/® have given it the surname of “ manicon.”” %0aThose, on the other hand, who have iniquitously concealed its %0areal qualities, give it the name of “ erythron” or “neuras,” %0aand others “perisson”—details, however, which need not be %0aentered into more fully, except for the purpose of putting %0apersons upon their guard. %0a%0aThere is another kind, again, also called “ halicacabum,'* %0awhich possesses narcotic qualities, and is productiv'e of death %0aeven more speedily than opium : by some persons it is called %0a“morio,” and by others “moly.”^® It has, how^ever, been %0ahighly extolled by Diodes and Evenor, and, indeed, Timaristus %0ahas gone so far as to sing its praises in verse. With a wonder¬ %0aful obliviousness of remedies really harmless, they tell us, for¬ %0asooth, that it is an instantaneous remedy for loose teeth to %0arinse them with halicacabuin steeped in wine : but at the same %0atime they add the qualification that it must not be kept in the %0amouth too long, or else delirium will be the result. This, how¬ %0aever, is pointing out remedies W'ith a vengeance, the employ¬ %0ament of which will be attended with worse results than the %0amalady itself. %0a%0aThere is a third kind^® of halicacahum, that is esteemed as an %0aarticle of food ; but even though the flavour of it may be pre¬ %0aferred to garden plants, and although Xenocrates assures us that %0athere is no bodily malady for which the trychnos is not highly %0abeneficial, they are none of them so valuable as to make me %0athink it proper to speak more at length upon the subject, more %0aparticularly as there are so many other remedies, which are %0aunattended with danger. Persons who wish to pass themselves %0aoff for true prophets, and who know too well how to impose %0a"upon the superstitions of others, take the root of the halicaca¬ %0ahum in drink. The remedy against this poison—and it is with %0amuch greater pleasure that I state it—is to driuk large quan¬ %0atities of honied wine made hot. I must not omit the fact, %0atoo, that this plant is naturally so baneful to the asp, that W'hen %0athe root is placed near that reptile, the very animal which %0akills others by striking them with torpor, is struck with torpor %0a%0a“ Apertius,” as suggested by Sillig, is a preferable reading to “ par- %0acius.” %0a%0aFrojn fiavia, “madness.” %0a%0a“ The Physalis somnifera of Linnaeus, the somniferous nightshade. %0a%0aThe Solauum melongena of Linnaeus. %0a%0aTOL. IV. C C %0a%0a%0a%0a38G pliny’s natubal nisTOur. [Book XXL %0a%0aitself; hence it is, that, beaten up with oil, it is used as a cure %0afor the sting of the asp. %0a%0aCHAP. 106. —SIX MEDICINES DERIVED FEOM THE COR- %0aCHORUS. %0a%0aThe corchorus^® is a plant which is used at Alexandria as an %0aarticle of food: the leaves of it are rolled up, one upon the %0aother, like those of the mulberry, and it is wholesome, it is %0asaid, for the viscera, and in cases of alopecy, being good also %0afor the removal of freckles. I find it stated also, that it cures %0athe scab in cattle very rapidly : and, according to Nicander,** %0ait is a remedy for the stings of serpents, if gathered before it %0ablossoms. %0a%0aCHAP. 107. —THREE REMEDIES DERIVED FROM THE CNECOS. %0a%0aThere would be no necessity to speak at any length of the %0acnecos or atractylis,^® an Egyptian plant, were it not for the fact %0athat it offers a most efficacious remedy for the stings of veno¬ %0amous animals, as also in cases of poisoning by fungi. It is %0aa well-known fact, that persons, whejn stung by the scorpion, %0aare not sensible of any painful effects so long as they hold this %0aplant in their hand. %0a%0aCHAP. 108. (33.) —ONE REMEDY DERIVED FROM THE %0aPESOLUTA. %0a%0aThe Egyptians also cultivate the pesoluta^® in their gardens, %0afor chaplets. There are two kinds of this plant, the male and %0athe female: either of them, it is said, placed beneath the per¬ %0ason, when in bed, acts 