diff:1673558067:1673558067:=1,5631d0%0a%3c BOOK XXL %0a%3c %0a%3c AN ACCOUNT OF FLOWERS, AND THOSE USED FOR %0a%3c CHAPLETS MORE PARTICULARLY. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP, 1 . ( 1 .) —the NATUKE OF FLOWERS AND GARLANDS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Cato has recommended that flow'ers for raaJring chaplets %0a%3c should also be cultivated in the garden ; varieties remarkable %0a%3c for a delicacy which it is quite impossible to express, inas¬ %0a%3c much as no individual can find such facilities for describing %0a%3c them as Nature does for bestowing on them their numerous tints %0a%3c —Nature, who here in especial shows herself in a sportive %0a%3c mood, and takes a delight in the prolific display of her varied %0a%3c productions. The other' plants she has produced for our use %0a%3c and our nutriment, and to them accordingly she has granted %0a%3c years and even ages of duration : but as for the fiowers and %0a%3c their perfumes, she has given them birth for but a day—a %0a%3c mighty lesson to man, we see, to teach him that that which in %0a%3c its career is the most beauteous and the most attractive to the %0a%3c eye, is the very first to fade and die. %0a%3c %0a%3c Even the limner’s art itself possesses no resources for re¬ %0a%3c producing the colours of the fiowers in all their varied tints %0a%3c and combinations, whether we view them in groups alter¬ %0a%3c nately blending their hues, or whether arranged in festoons, each %0a%3c variety by * itself, now assuming a circular form, now running %0a%3c obliquely, and now disposed in a spiral pattern ; or whether, %0a%3c as we see sometimes, one wreath is interwoven within another. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 2 . ( 2 .) —GARLANDS AND CHAPLETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c The ancients used chaplets of diminutive size, called %0a%3c “ struppifrom which comes our name for a chaplet, “ stro- %0a%3c %0a%3c * See B. xxii. c. 1. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 “ Sive privatis generum funiculis in orbem, in obliquum, in ambitnm ; %0a%3c quaedam coronae per coronas currunt.” As we know