r additional honour %0a%3c on them, lemnisci were added, in imitation of the Etruscan %0a%3c chaplets, which ought properly to have none but lemnisci %0a%3c made of gold. For a long period these lemnisci were desti¬ %0a%3c tute of ornament P. Claudius Pulcher*® was the first who %0a%3c taught us to emboss*® them, and added leaves of tinsel to the %0a%3c laminee®® of which the lemniscus was formed. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 5 . —THE GREAT HONOUR IN WHICH CHAPLETS WERE HELD %0a%3c BY THE ANCIENTS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Chaplets, however, were always held in a high degree of %0a%3c estimation, those even which were acquired at the public %0a%3c games. For it was the usage of the citizens to go down in %0a%3c person to take part in the contests of the Circus, and to %0a%3c send their slaves and horses thither as well. Hence it is that %0a%3c we find it thus written in the laws of the Twelve Tables: %0a%3c %0a%3c 12 From Atlienoeus, B. xv. c. 2, et seq., we learn that the Egyptian %0a%3c chaplets were made of ivy, narcissus, pomegranate blossoms, &c. %0a%3c %0a%3c ‘2 “Corolla,” being the diminutive of “corona.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 1* Or tinsel. is The “ Rich.” %0a%3c %0a%3c IS Ribbons or streamers. i^ “Puri.” %0a%3c %0a%3c IS Consul, A.u.c. 570. %0a%3c %0a%3c IS Or “engrave,” “caelare.” Jle is probably speaking here of golden %0a%3c lemnisci. %0a%3c %0a%3c 20 “ Philyr®.” This was properly the inner bark of the linden-tree; %0a%3c but it is not improbable that thin plates of metal were also so called, from %0a%3c che resemblance. The passage, however, admits of various modes of ex¬ %0a%3c planation. %0a%3c %0a%3c *• 1 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 6.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAPLETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 307 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c “ If any person has gained a chaplet himself, or by his %0a%3c money,** let the same be given to him as the reward of his %0a%3c prowess.” There is no doubt that by the words “ gained by %0a%3c his money,” the laws meant a chaplet which had been gained %0a%3c by his slaves or horses. Well then, what was the honour ac¬ %0a%3c quired thereby ? It was the right secured bythe victor, for %0a%3c himself and for his parents, after death, to be crowned with¬ %0a%3c out fail, while the body was laid out in the house,** and on its %0a%3c being carried** to the tomb. %0a%3c %0a%3c On other occasions, chaplets were not indiscriminately %0a%3c worn, not even those which had been won in the games. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 6.-THE SEVERITY OF THE AHCIEHTS IN REFERENCE TO %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAPLETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Indeed the rules upon this point were remarkably severe. %0a%3c L. Fulvius, a banker,** having been accused, at the time of %0a%3c the Second Punic War, of looking down from the balcony*® %0a%3c of his house upon the Forum, with a chaplet of roses upon %0a%3c his head, was imprisoned by order of the Senate, and was not %0a%3c liberated before the war was brought to a close. P. Muna- %0a%3c tius, having placed upon his head a chaplet of flowers taken %0a%3c from the statue of Marsyas,*® was condemned by the Trium¬ %0a%3c viri to be put in chains. Upon his making appeal to the %0a%3c tribunes of the people, they refused to intercede in his behalf %0a%3c —a very different state of things to that at Athens, where %0a%3c the young men,*’ in their dnmken revelry, were in the habit, %0a%3c %0a%3c ** “ Pecunia.” Fee compares this usage with the employment of jockies %0a%3c at horse-races in England and France. %0a%3c %0a%3c “ Intus positus esset.” •* “ Foris ferretur.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 2* Or “ money-changer,” ‘‘ argentarius.” %0a%3c %0a%3c “ “E pergula sua.” Scaliger thinks that the “pergula” was a part %0a%3c of a house built out into the street, while, according to Ernesti,^ it was a %0a%3c little room in the upper part of a house. In B. xxxv. c. 36, it clearly %0a%3c means a room on the ground-floor. %0a%3c %0a%3c 26 In the Fora of ancient cities there was frequently a statue of this my¬ %0a%3c thological personage, with one hand erect, in token, Servius says (on %0a%3c B. iv. 1. 58 of the iEneid), of the freedom of the state, Marsyas having been %0a%3c the minister of Bacchus, the god of liberty. His statue in the Forum of %0a%3c Rome was the place of assembly for the courtesans of that city, who used %0a%3c to crown it with chaplets ot flow’crs. See also Horace i. Sat. 6. 1. 120; %0a%3c Juvenal, Sat. 9. 1. 1 and 2; and Martial,ii. Ep. 64.1. 7. %0a%3c %0a%3c 27 Ciijacius thinks that Pliny has in view here Polemon of Athens, who %0a%3c when a young man, in his drunken revelry, burst into the school of Xeno- %0a%3c cratcs. the philosopher, with his fellow-revellers, wearing his festive gar- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLIXT’S XATUKAIi lIISrOKT. [Book XXI. %0a%3c %0a%3c before midday, of making their way into the very schools of %0a%3c the philosophers even. Among ourselves, no such instance of %0a%3c a similar licentiousness is lo be found, unless, indeed, in the %0a%3c case of the daughter*® of the late Emperor Augustus, who, in %0a%3c her nocturnal debaucheries, placed a chaplet on the statue^* %0a%3c of JIarsyas, conduct deeply deplored in the letters of that %0a%3c god.®" %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 7.-A CITIZEN DECKED WITH FLOWEES BY THE HOMAN %0a%3c %0a%3c PEOPLE. %0a%3c %0a%3c Scipio is the only person that ever received from the Eoman %0a%3c people the honour of being decked with flowers. This %0a%3c Scipio received the surname of Serapio,®^ from his remarkable %0a%3c resemblance to a certain person of that name who dealt in %0a%3c pigs. He died in his tribuneship, greatly beloved by the %0a%3c people, and in every way worthy of the family of the African!. %0a%3c The property he left was not sufficient to pay the expenses of %0a%3c his burial; upon which the people made a subscription and %0a%3c contracted®* for his funeral, flowers being scattered upon the %0a%3c body from every possible quarter®® as it was borne along. %0a%3c %0a%3c CUAP. 8. — PLAITED CHAPLETS. NEEDLE-WORK CHAPLETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c NARD-LEAF CHAPLETS. SILKEN CHAPLETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c In those days, too, chaplets were employed in honour of the %0a%3c gods, the Lares, public as well as domestic, the sepulchres,®* %0a%3c and the Manes. The highest place, however, in public esti¬ %0a%3c mation, was held by the plaited chaplet; such as we find used %0a%3c %0a%3c land on his head. Being arrested, however, by the discourse, he stopped %0a%3c to listen, and at length, tearing off the garland, determined to enter on a %0a%3c more abstemious course of life. Becoming an ardent disciple of Xeno- %0a%3c crates, he ultimately succeeded him at the head of the school. The pas¬ %0a%3c sage as given in the text, from its apparent incompleteness, would appear %0a%3c to he in a mutilated state. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ Julia. See B. vii. c. 46. %0a%3c %0a%3c *9 Thus acknowledging herself to be no better than a common courtesan. %0a%3c “ lUius dei.” 3‘ See B. vii. c. 10. %0a%3c %0a%3c 32 “ Funus elocavit.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 “ E prospectu omni.” “ From every look-out i.e. from the roofs, %0a%3c doors, and windows. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3* This usage is still observed in the immortelles, laid on the tombs of %0a%3c departed friends, in Catholic countries on the continent. Tibullus alludes %0a%3c to it, B. ii. El. 4: %0a%3c %0a%3c “ Atque aliquis senior veteres veneratus amores, %0a%3c %0a%3c Annua constructo serta dabit tumulo.” %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 9.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAPLETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 309 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c by tlie Salii in their sacred rites, and at the solemnization of %0a%3c their yearly^® banquets. In later times, the rose chaplet has %0a%3c been adopted, and luxury arose at last to such a pitch that a %0a%3c chaplet was held in no esteem at all if it did not consist en¬ %0a%3c tirely of leaves sown together with the needle. More recently, %0a%3c again, they have been imported from India, or from nations %0a%3c beyond the countries of India. %0a%3c %0a%3c But it is looked upon as the most refined of all, to present %0a%3c chaplets made of nard leaves, or else of silk of many colours %0a%3c steeped in unguents. Such is the pitch to which the luxu¬ %0a%3c riousness of our women has at last arrived! %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 9.-AHTHORS WHO HAVE WRITTEN ON FLOWERS. AN %0a%3c %0a%3c ANECDOTE RELATIVE TO Q0EEN CLEOPATRA AND CHAPLETS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Among the Greeks, the physicians Mnesitheus and Calli¬ %0a%3c machus have written separate treatises on the subject of %0a%3c chaplets, making mention of such flowers as are injurious to %0a%3c the head.®® For, in fact, the health is here concerned to some %0a%3c extent, as it is at the moments of carousal and gaiety in par¬ %0a%3c ticular that penetrating odours steal insidiously upon the %0a%3c brain—witness an instance in the wicked cunning displayed %0a%3c upon one occasion by Cleopatra. %0a%3c %0a%3c At the time when preparations were making for the battle %0a%3c that was eventually fought at Actiura, Antonius held the %0a%3c queen in such extreme distrust as to be in dread of her very %0a%3c attentions even, and would not so much as touch his food, %0a%3c unless another person had tasted it first. Upon this, the %0a%3c queen, it is said, wishing to amuse herself with his fears, had %0a%3c - the extremities of the flowers in a chaplet dipped in poison, and %0a%3c then placed it upon her head.®^ After a time, as the hilarity %0a%3c increased apace, she challenged Antonius to swallow the chap¬ %0a%3c es At the conclusion of the festival of Mars on the 1st of March, and %0a%3c for several successive days. These entertainments were celebrated in the %0a%3c Temple of that god, and were proverbial for their excellence. %0a%3c %0a%3c “ It is a well-known fact, as Fee remarks, that the smell of flowers is %0a%3c productive, in some persons, of head-ache, nausea, and vertigo. He states %0a%3c also that persons have been known to meet their death from sleeping all %0a%3c night in the midst of odoriferous flowers. %0a%3c %0a%3c “Ipsaque capiti imposita.” Holland and Ajasson render this as %0a%3c tlioimh Cleopatra placed the garland on Antony’s head, and not her owu. %0a%3c Littr'^ agrees with the translation here adopted. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 310 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Pliny’s natubal histoey. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [nook XXI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c lets, mixed up with their drink. Who, under such circumstances %0a%3c as these, could have apprehended treachery? Accordingly, %0a%3c the leaves were stripped from off the chaplet, and thrown into %0a%3c ihe cup. Just as Antonius was on the very point of drinking, %0a%3c she arrested his arm with her hand.—“ Behold, Marcus An¬ %0a%3c tonius,” said she, “ the woman against whom you are so care¬ %0a%3c ful to take these new precautions of yours in employing your %0a%3c tasters! And would then, if I could exist without you, either %0a%3c means or opportunity of effecting my purpose be wanting to %0a%3c me?” Saying this, she ordered a man to be brought from %0a%3c prison, and made him drink off the potion; he did so, and %0a%3c fell dead®® upon the spot. %0a%3c %0a%3c Besides the two authors above-mentioned, Theophrastus,®* %0a%3c among the Greeks, has written on the subject of flowers. %0a%3c Some of our own writers also have given the title of “ Antho- %0a%3c logica” to their works, but no one, to my knowledge at least, %0a%3c has treated expressly^® of flowers. In fact, we ourselves have %0a%3c no intention here of discussing the mode of wearing chaplets, %0a%3c for that would be frivolous^^ indeed ; but shall proceed to %0a%3c state such particulars in relation to flowers as shall appear to %0a%3c us deserving of remark. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 10 . ( 4 .) —THE EOSE : TWELVE VAEIETIES OF IT. %0a%3c %0a%3c The people of our country were acquainted with but very %0a%3c few garland flowers among the garden plants, and those few %0a%3c hardly any but the violet and the rose. The plant which bears %0a%3c the rose is, properly speaking, more of a thorn than a shrub— %0a%3c indeed, we sometimes find it growing on a bramble^* even; %0a%3c the flower having, even then, a pleasant smell, though by no %0a%3c means penetrating. The flower in all roses is originally en¬ %0a%3c closed in a bud,^® with a grained surface within, which gra¬ %0a%3c dually swells, and assumes the form of a green pointed cone, %0a%3c similar to our alabaster^^ unguent boxes in shape. Gradually %0a%3c %0a%3c Fee remarks that we know of no poisons, hydrocyanic or prussic acid %0a%3c excepted, so instantaneous in their effects as this; and that it is very %0a%3c doubtful if they were acquainted with that poison. %0a%3c %0a%3c Hist. Plant. B. vi. cc. 6, 7. “ Persecutus est.” %0a%3c %0a%3c A characteristic, it would appear, of the greater part of the inform¬ %0a%3c ation already given in this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c He alludes to the wild rose or eglantine. See B. xvi. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c “ Granoso cortice.” %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ Boxes of a pyramidal shape. See B. ix. c. 56. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 10.1 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE HOSE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 311 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c acquiring a ruddy tint, this bud opens little by little, until at %0a%3c last it comes into full blow, developing the calyx, and em¬ %0a%3c bracing the yellow-pointed filaments which stand erect in the %0a%3c centre of it. %0a%3c %0a%3c The employment of the rose in chaplets is, so to say, the %0a%3c least^® use that is made of it. The flower is steeped in oil, a %0a%3c practice which has prevailed from the times of the Trojan war, %0a%3c as Homer‘® bears witness; in addition to which, it now forms %0a%3c an ingredient in our unguents, as mentioned on a previous %0a%3c occasion.^^ It is employed also by itself for certain medicinal %0a%3c purposes, and is used in plasters and eye-salves^* for its pene¬ %0a%3c trating qualities : it is used, also, to perfume the delicacies of %0a%3c our banquets, and is never attended with any noxious results. %0a%3c %0a%3c The most esteemed kinds of rose among us are those of %0a%3c Prseneste'** and Campania.®* Some persons have added to these %0a%3c varieties the rose of Miletus,®^ the flower of which is an ex¬ %0a%3c tremely brilliant red, and has never more than a dozen petals. %0a%3c The next to it is the rose of TrachjTi,®* not so red as the last, %0a%3c and then that of Alabanda,®® with whitish petals, but not so %0a%3c highly esteemed. The least esteemed of all, however, is the %0a%3c thorn rose,®^ the petals of which are numerous, but extremely %0a%3c %0a%3c Still, even for that purpose the rose Avas very extensively used. One %0a%3c ancient author states that, even in the middle of winter, the more luxurious %0a%3c liomans were not satisfied without roses swimming in their Falernian wine; %0a%3c and we find Horace repeatedly alluding to the chaplets of roses worn by %0a%3c the guests at banquets. Hence probably arose the expression, “Under %0a%3c the rose.” Fee is evidently mistaken in thinking that Pliny implies here, %0a%3c that it was but rarely used in chaplets. %0a%3c %0a%3c II. xxiii. 1. 186. B. xiii. c. 2. %0a%3c %0a%3c “Collyriis.” %0a%3c %0a%3c Clusius Avas of opinion that this was the Provence rose, the Rosa %0a%3c Gallica of Uinnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c The same rose, probably, of which Virgil says, Georg. B. iv. 1. 119, %0a%3c “ Bifcrique rosaria Paesti”—" And the rose-beds of Paestum, that bear %0a%3c twice in the year.” It has been suggested that it is identical with the %0a%3c Bosa alba vulgaris major of Bauhin, the Rosa alba of Decandolle; but, %0a%3c as F4e says, it is very questionable if this is correct, this white rose blossom¬ %0a%3c ing but once a year. _ . i i %0a%3c %0a%3c A simple variety of the Rosa Gallica of Linnaeus, Fee thinks. %0a%3c %0a%3c See B. iv. c. 14. According to J. Bauhin, this is the pale, flesh- %0a%3c coloured rose, called the “ rose of France,”—the “ Rosa rubello flore, %0a%3c majore, pleno, incarnata vulgo.’’ Others, again, take it to be the Damascus %0a%3c rose. %0a%3c %0a%3c “ Sec B. V. c. 29. A varie