maedaphne.” %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 40. —THE DCEATION OF LIFE IN THE VAEIOHS KINDS OF %0a%3c FLOWERS. %0a%3c %0a%3c At the very utmost, the white®^ violet never lasts longer %0a%3c than three years : should it exceed tliat period, it is sure to %0a%3c degenerate. The rose-tree will last so long as five years with¬ %0a%3c out being pruned or cauterized,®® methods by which it is made %0a%3c to grow young again. We have already stated®® that the na¬ %0a%3c ture of the soil is of the very greatest importance; for in %0a%3c Egypt, we find, all these plants are perfectly inodorous, and %0a%3c it is only the myrtle that has an)" particular smell. In some %0a%3c countries, too, the germination of all the plants precedes that %0a%3c in other parts of the world b)" so long a period as two months %0a%3c even. The rose-beds should be W"ell spaded immediately after %0a%3c the west winds begin to prevail, and, a second time, at the %0a%3c summer solstice : every care, however, should be paid, between %0a%3c these two periods, to keeping the ground well raked and %0a%3c cleaned. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 41. (12.) —PLANTS WHICH SHOULD BE SOWN AMONG %0a%3c FLOWERS FOR BEES. THE CERINTHA. %0a%3c %0a%3c Bees and beehives, too, are a subject extremely well suited %0a%3c to a description of gardens and garland plants, while, at the %0a%3c same time, where they are successfully managed, they" are a %0a%3c source, without any great outlay, of very considerable profit. %0a%3c For bees, then, the following plants should be grown—thyme, %0a%3c apiastrum, the rose, the various violets, the lily, the cytisus, %0a%3c the bean, the fitch, cunila, the poppy, conyza,®’ cassia, the me- %0a%3c %0a%3c Linnaeus and other authorities identify this with the Clematis of %0a%3c Dioscorides, the Vinca major and minor of modern botany, our periwinkle. %0a%3c Fee, however, is inclined to identify it with the Chamaedaphne, or ground- %0a%3c laurel of B. XV. c. 39, the Ruscus raceraosus of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c ®* See c. 38 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c ®® This method of cultivation, also mentioned by Theophrastus, is never %0a%3c employed in modern horticulture. %0a%3c %0a%3c *® In c. 10 of this Book. See B. xix. c. 50. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 340 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXI, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c lilote, melissophyllum,®* and the cerintha.®* This last is a plant %0a%3c with a white leaf, heut inwards, the stem of it being a cubit %0a%3c in height, with a flower at the top presenting a concavity full %0a%3c of a juice like hone)'. Bees are remarkably fond of the flowers %0a%3c of these plants, as also the blossoms of mustard, a thing that %0a%3c is somewhat surprising, seeing that it is a w'ell-known fact that %0a%3c they will not so much as touch the blossoms of the olive: for %0a%3c which reason, it will be as well to keep that tree at a distance %0a%3c from them.™ %0a%3c %0a%3c There are other trees, again, w'hich should be planted as %0a%3c near the hives as possible, as they attract the swarm when it %0a%3c first w'ings its flight, and so prevent the bees from wandering %0a%3c to any considerable distance. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 42. -THE MALADIES OF BEES, AND THE REMEDIES FOR %0a%3c %0a%3c THEM. %0a%3c %0a%3c The greatest care, too, should be taken to keep the comeP' %0a%3c at a distance from the hives; for if the bees once taste the %0a%3c blossoms of it, they w'ill speedily die of flux and looseness. %0a%3c The best remedy in such case is to give them sorb apples %0a%3c beaten up with honey, or else human urine or that of oxen, or %0a%3c pomegranate seeds moistened with Aminean™ wine. It is a %0a%3c very good plan, too, to plant broom about the hives, the bees %0a%3c being extremely foud of the blossoms. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 43. —THE FOOD OF BEES. %0a%3c %0a%3c In relation to the food of bees, I have ascertained a very %0a%3c singular fact, and one that well deserves to be mentioned. %0a%3c %0a%3c “ Honey-leaf.” The Melissa oflBcin